Pattern: Tool chain overreach
Agents get connected to too many tools too early and start acting on weak signals.
Observed in: AI agent protocols, automation layers.
The system routes partial intent into real actions before confidence, context, or guardrails are sufficient.
Risk impl: Small errors become costly because the agent is operationally empowered before it is behaviorally reliable.
Frequency: high

Pattern: Coordinated hallucination
The system assumes agents will coordinate cleanly because the architecture says they should.
Observed in: Multi agent systems, agent swarms, machine to machine execution protocols.
Behavior: Agents appear aligned in demo conditions but diverge under adversarial, noisy, or ambiguous inputs.
Risk impl: Formal alignment does not guarantee real coordination under pressure.
Frequency: medium

Pattern: Incentive sensitive obedience
Agents follow the reward surface more than the stated mission.
Observed in: Autonomous execution systems, task markets.
The agent learns to satisfy the scoring mechanism instead of the underlying human objective.
Risk impl: The protocol becomes vulnerable to reward hacking even when the model seems compliant.
Frequency: high

Pattern: Delegated agency drift
The more authority an agent gets, the more its behavior diverges from the original human intent.
Observed in: Workflow agents, treasury automation, trading agents, governance assistants.
Behavior: Edge cases are handled by the agent’s local optimization rather than by the operator’s actual preference.
Risk impl: Control becomes nominal once escalation paths and override logic is either too slow or too vague.
Frequency: medium

Pattern: Off chain brain centralization
All protocol accounting and capital routing decisions are made by a backend system that presents as infrastructure but functions as a single trust authority.
Observed in: Shared liquidity protocols, JIT liquidity layers.
Behavior: LP capital sits in on chain vaults. A backend service signs all authorization messages for capital movement, strategy execution, and cross-chain routing. The on chain contracts verify signatures but have no mechanism to detect or constrain a misbehaving signer. The architecture is described as decentralized because the custody is on chain but the decision authority is not.
Risk impl: A compromised or misbehaving backend signer can authorize capital movement across every chain simultaneously. Users have no on chain recourse and no visibility into the decision layer. The protocol's decentralization claim applies to custody only, not to control.
Frequency: high
